{"query": "What are the documented benefits and potential drawbacks of reducing tillage on European farmland?", "summary": "Based on 42 individual studies from European countries including Belgium, Denmark, France, Germany, Hungary, Ireland, Lithuania, the Netherlands, Slovakia, Switzerland and the UK, reducing tillage on European farmland shows several documented benefits and drawbacks.

Benefits include: increased earthworm biomass, species richness and abundance (Action 126); greater abundance of some invertebrates other than earthworms (Action 126); increased numbers of some weeds and weed species (Action 126); higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying date and shorter foraging distances on reduced tillage fields (Action 126); greater abundance of some birds including Eurasian skylark, seed-eating songbirds and gamebirds in late winter on non-inversion or conservation tillage (Action 126); more invertebrate bird food resources in no-till systems (Action 126); higher soil organic carbon in soils under no-tillage or reduced tillage systems compared to conventionally tilled soil (Action 906); maintained or increased soil organic matter and improved soil structure under reduced tillage (Action 906); higher nutrient retention under reduced tillage (Action 906); reduced soil loss and runoff under reduced tillage compared to conventional ploughing (Action 906); and higher species richness or diversity for some bird groups on reduced-tillage fields (Action 211).

Drawbacks and negative effects include: negative effects, no effect or no consistent effects on abundance, biomass, or species richness of some invertebrates other than earthworms (Action 126); no effect on earthworm abundance, biomass, or species richness in some studies (Action 126); decreased bird preferences for conservation tillage fields over time (Action 126); higher compaction under reduced tillage in some cases (Action 906); increased soil loss in no-tillage systems when crop cover is absent (Action 906); lower yields under minimum or no-tillage compared to conventional tillage in some studies (Action 906); and some measures of bird diversity being lower or no different on reduced-tillage fields compared to conventional fields (Action 211).", "action_ids": ["126","906","211","789","11","3488"]}

