{
  "action_id": "69",
  "action_title": "Reduce management intensity on permanent grasslands (several interventions at once)",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nA total of 32 individual studies from the Czech Republic, Germany, Ireland, the Netherlands, Switzerland and the UK looked at the effects on farmland wildlife of reducing management intensity on permanent grasslands. Twenty-two studies found benefits to some or all wildlife groups studied. Eleven studies (including four replicated site comparisons and three reviews) found reduced management intensity on permanent grassland benefited plants. Sixteen studies (including eight site comparisons of which four paired and three reviews) found benefits to some or all invertebrates. Five studies (including two replicated site comparisons, of which one paired, and a review) found positive effects on some or all birds.\nTwenty-one studies from six European countries found no clear effects of reducing management intensity on some or all plants, invertebrates or birds. Seven studies (including two replicated paired site comparisons and a review) found no clear effect on plants. Ten studies (including four site comparisons and one paired site comparison) found mixed or no effects on some or all invertebrates. Two studies (one review, one site comparison) found invertebrate communities on less intensively managed grasslands were distinct from those on intensively managed grasslands. Four studies (including three site comparisons, of which one paired and two replicated) found no clear effects on bird numbers or species richness.\nFive studies from four European countries found negative effects of reducing management intensity on plants, invertebrates or birds. Two studies (one review, one replicated trial) found some plant species were lost under extensive management. Two studies (one paired site comparison) found more invertebrates in grasslands with intensive management. One paired site comparison found fewer wading birds on grasslands with reduced management intensity than on conventionally managed grassland."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query": "In European agricultural landscapes, what management techniques are available to restore or create species-rich wet meadows?", "summary": "Based on the evidence from European studies, several management techniques are available to restore or create species-rich wet meadows in agricultural landscapes. From studies across France, Germany, the Netherlands, Poland, Switzerland and the UK, successful restoration techniques include topsoil removal, introduction of target plant species, raising water levels, grazing, mowing, or combinations of topsoil removal with target plant species introduction plus livestock exclusion (Action 119). Water level management is particularly important, with raising water levels in ditches or grassland showing positive effects on bird numbers, plant species that favour wet conditions, and invertebrate numbers in agricultural landscapes, though some studies found net loss of plant species (Action 121). Active water level management, including controlled flooding and water fluctuation, can generate plant communities characteristic of wetter conditions and increase wetland-characteristic species abundance (Action 3038).

Traditional water meadow maintenance involves specific management regimes including grazing and mowing. Mowing once per year in autumn or light grazing with cattle or horses produces similar butterfly species richness (Action 3971). Grazing management shows mixed impacts, with some studies finding benefits for certain species but reduced productivity for others. Studies indicate that cutting in June maintained relatively stable vegetation, while mowing effects on plant species richness were variable (Action 696). For general grassland restoration, effective techniques include grazing, introducing plant species, hay spreading and mowing, with positive restoration signs typically visible within 5-10 years (Action 133).

Management intensity reduction through several interventions shows benefits, with 22 studies finding positive effects on wildlife groups including plants, invertebrates and birds, though results can be variable depending on the specific interventions applied (Action 69). The timing and type of management is crucial, with species-rich grasslands showing different responses to mowing versus grazing regimes depending on the target species and local conditions (Action 3908).", "action_ids": ["119","3971","696","121","133","3038","69","3908"]}

