{
  "query": "For the benefit of farmland birds, what is the comparative evidence for sowing crops in spring versus leaving stubbles overwinter?",
  "relevant_summary": "The evidence shows benefits for farmland birds from both spring sowing and overwinter stubbles, with some specific comparative findings. For overwinter stubbles, eighteen studies found evidence that leaving overwinter stubbles provides benefits to farmland birds, including higher densities of farmland birds in winter, increased grey partridge productivity, and increased cirl bunting population size (Action 695). Eight studies found that at least some species or groups of farmland birds were positively associated with overwinter stubbles, with seed-eating birds in particular being more abundant on stubbles (Action 203). However, some studies found that only certain species benefited - one study found that only Eurasian skylark and Eurasian linnet benefited out of 23 farmland bird species tested, while another found only grey partridge and tree sparrow showed positive population responses (Action 695). For spring sowing, a replicated controlled study from Sweden found more bird species on areas with spring sown cereals compared with winter cereals, and a UK study found several species bred in the study site for the first time after spring sowing began (Action 207). Three studies found population increases after spring sowing began or higher populations on sites with spring-sown cereals compared to sites with winter cereals (Action 207). Five studies found that planting crops in spring rather than autumn resulted in higher numbers of farmland birds (Action 137). However, a replicated study found that winter and spring sown crops were used for different broods by Eurasian skylarks, and hatching success was lower on spring-sown crops than autumn sown (Actions 137, 207). The evidence suggests both practices provide different types of benefits to farmland birds, with overwinter stubbles particularly benefiting seed-eating birds during winter, while spring sowing appears to support breeding bird communities.",
