{"query": "When undertaking habitat restoration on farmland, such as creating species-rich grassland, what is the typical timeframe for seeing positive ecological changes?", "summary": "Based on evidence from multiple studies on grassland restoration, the timeframe for seeing positive ecological changes varies significantly. Six studies saw positive signs of restoration in less than five years, while 11 studies found positive changes within 10 years (Action 133). Two studies found restoration took more than 10 years, and six studies found limited or slow changes in plant communities following restoration (Action 133). 

More specifically, prairies restored 5-10 years ago by seeding with native species, mowing, and weeding or applying herbicide had greater abundance of certain butterfly species than prairies restored 1-2 years ago, and similar abundance to remnant prairies (Action 3943). Grasslands restored from bare soil by seeding developed butterfly communities that were increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment (Action 3929). Studies found that 4-5-year-old created grasslands had greater species richness of butterflies, burnet moths and all moths than conventionally managed grassland (Action 3929).

However, some differences persist over longer periods - two studies found differences in vegetation between restored and existing species-rich grasslands nine or 60 years after restoration (Action 133). The species richness of butterflies on restored grasslands remained similar over time since restoration, showing stability once established (Action 3955). Over 10 years after restoration, the number of butterfly species on seeded grassland remained similar each year (Action 3929).", "action_ids": ["133","3943","3929","3955"]}

