{
  "query": "What are the overall effects of broad-scale agri-environment schemes on farmland biodiversity in Europe?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on evidence from European studies, agri-environment schemes show mixed but generally positive effects on farmland biodiversity. For birds, 24 out of 26 studies from four European countries found increases in population size, density or more favourable population trends of some or all birds studied on sites with agri-environment schemes compared to non-scheme sites, though 11 studies found negative or no effects (Action 700). Three reviews from the UK reported population increases of three species (cirl buntings, corncrakes and Eurasian thick-knees) after introduction of specially-designed agri-environment schemes (Action 172). For plants, 7 out of 11 studies from five European countries found agri-environment schemes maintained or had little or no effect on plants, plant diversity or species richness, while three studies found increases in plant species richness and two found decreases (Action 700). For invertebrates, 6 out of 10 studies from three European countries showed agri-environment schemes maintained or had little or no effect on some invertebrates in terms of diversity, abundance, species richness or bee colony growth, while five studies found increases in abundance or species richness of some invertebrates (Action 700). Specifically for wild bees, four replicated trials in Europe showed enhanced diversity and/or abundance of foraging wild bees on land managed under various European agri-environment schemes, but four other replicated trials found that the number of bees and/or bee species was not enhanced (Action 24). For amphibians, one replicated study in the Netherlands found that ditches managed under agri-environment schemes had higher numbers of amphibian species and higher abundance than conventionally managed ditches (Action 818). A European review found that two out of three agri-environment schemes in Europe benefited wildlife (Action 700).",
