  "query": "For managing heather moorland in the UK, what is the comparative evidence for the effectiveness of swiping versus controlled burning on plant diversity?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the available evidence, a replicated controlled trial in Northern Ireland directly compared the effectiveness of swiping (flailing) versus controlled burning on plant diversity in heather moorland (Action 151, 152). The study found that eight years after management, heather moorland subject to flailing to simulate burning had more plant species than control unflailed plots, but fewer plant species than burned plots (Action 151). Additionally, heather moorland subject to a single burn had more plant species eight years after the management than control unburned plots (Action 152). This indicates that controlled burning was more effective than swiping for increasing plant species diversity in heather moorland. A systematic review of five studies from the UK found that prescribed burning did not alter species diversity, though a before and after study found that prescribed burning initially decreased the cover of most plant species, but their cover subsequently increased (Action 1625). A replicated, controlled study in the UK found that regeneration of heather was similar in cut and burned areas (Action 1625).",
