  "relevant_summary": "Undersowing spring cereals as an alternative to conventional ploughing provides several wildlife benefits. Eleven studies found that undersowing spring cereals benefited some birds, plants, insects, spiders and earthworms (Action 136). These benefits included increases in barnacle goose abundance, densities of singing Eurasian skylark and nesting dunnock, arthropod abundance and species richness, and bumblebee, butterfly, earthworm, ground beetle, spider or springtail abundances (Action 136). For butterflies specifically, spring barley undersown with a mix of grasses and legumes had higher species richness and abundance of butterflies than extensively or conventionally managed grassland (Action 3926). Studies found higher densities of some study species on undersown fields or margins compared with other fields, or that use of fields increased after they were undersown (Action 208). However, some studies showed mixed results, with five studies finding that undersowing spring cereals did not benefit invertebrates, plants, grey partridge population indicators, or nesting densities of two out of three farmland bird species (Action 136). Compared to conventional tillage practices, reduced tillage systems provide increased biomass, species richness or abundance of earthworms, greater abundance of some invertebrates, increased numbers of some weeds, higher Eurasian skylark nest density, earlier laying date and shorter foraging distances on reduced tillage fields (Action 126).",
