  "relevant_summary": "Studies show that both supplementary feeding and wild bird seed mixtures provide benefits for farmland birds, but they have different effectiveness patterns. For supplementary feeding, nine studies from France, Sweden and the UK found that provision of supplementary food increased farmland bird abundance, breeding population size, density, body mass, hatching, nestling growth and fledging rates, and increased overwinter survival of a declining house sparrow population (Action 648). Four studies found that farmland songbirds used supplementary food when provided, including the majority of targeted species such as tree sparrow, yellowhammer and corn bunting (Action 648). However, five studies found that supplementary food had no clear effect on farmland bird breeding abundance, territory size or territory density, or overwinter survival of three stable house sparrow populations (Action 648).\n\nFor wild bird seed mixtures, fourteen studies from the UK found that fields sown with wild bird cover mix had higher abundance, density, species diversity and species richness of birds than other farmland habitats (Action 594). Six studies found that birds showed a preference for wild bird cover and used it significantly more than other habitats (Action 594). All seven studies that investigated species richness or diversity found that fields or farms with wild bird cover had higher bird diversity than those without (Action 187). Thirty-two out of 33 studies from the UK and North America found that bird densities, abundances, nesting densities or use of wild bird cover was higher than in other habitats or management regimes (Action 187). Six studies found that mixtures including kale or a mixture of kale and other species attracted the largest number of bird species or highest bird abundance (Action 594).",
