{
  "query": "Following the restoration of grassland from other land uses on European farmland, what is the typical timeframe to see changes in plant communities?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on 22 studies from seven European countries that included information on the length of time taken to restore grassland communities, there are varying timeframes for observing changes in plant communities following grassland restoration. Six studies saw positive signs of restoration in less than five years (Action 133). Eleven studies found restoration occurred within 10 years, and two studies found restoration took more than 10 years (Action 133). However, six studies found limited or slow changes in plant communities following restoration (Action 133). Some studies indicated that grasslands restored from bare soil by seeding developed butterfly communities that were increasingly similar to existing high-quality grasslands over the first 10 years after establishment (Action 3929). Additionally, studies monitoring wet meadow plant communities found some positive effects within five years, though restoration was not complete after five, nine or 20 years in some cases (Action 119). Two studies found differences in vegetation between restored and existing species-rich grasslands persisted nine or 60 years after restoration (Action 133).",
