{"query": "In the Netherlands, what are the most effective management strategies for increasing wading bird populations on wet grasslands?", "summary": "Based on studies from the Netherlands, several management strategies have proven effective for increasing wading bird populations on wet grasslands. Maintaining traditional water meadows resulted in increased population size or number of territories of northern lapwing, common redshank and black-tailed godwit (Action 696). Raising water levels in ditches or grassland was associated with increased bird numbers and breeding bird numbers, with studies showing this technique resulted in more rapid establishment of species typical of wet grassland (Action 121). 

Implementing 'mosaic management', a Dutch agri-environment option, showed that northern lapwing population trends changed from decreases to increases following introduction of this management approach, and black-tailed godwit had higher productivity under mosaic management due to higher nest survival with nests less likely to be trampled by livestock or destroyed by mowing (Action 130). Creating or restoring traditional water meadows through techniques including topsoil removal, introduction of target plant species, raising water levels, grazing, and mowing were successful in restoring wet meadow plant communities (Action 119).

Additional effective strategies include delaying mowing or first grazing dates, which resulted in increased breeding wading bird densities (Action 131). Creating scrapes and pools in wetlands and wet grasslands showed that northern lapwing chicks foraged in newly created wet features and chick condition was higher in sites with a large number of footdrains (Action 359). Providing short grass for waders was beneficial, as northern lapwings spent more time foraging on short swards compared to longer grass (Action 221). Direct payments per clutch for farmland birds showed slightly higher breeding densities of wading birds and higher hatching success of northern lapwing and black-tailed godwit on farms with payment schemes (Action 146). Finally, protecting individual nests through exclosures showed that protected nests had higher average daily survival rates than unprotected nests for both common redshank and northern lapwing (Action 108).", "action_ids": ["696","121","130","119","131","359","221","146","108"]}

